    id: "f-rmc2-01",
    title: "The Great Charity Bake Sale",
    text: "When our head teacher announced that the school hall roof needed urgent repairs and that the local children's hospice was also short of funds, our class decided to organise a bake sale that would split the money between the two causes. I volunteered to coordinate it, mostly because nobody else put their hand up quickly enough, and within a day I regretted it. I had imagined a simple table of cupcakes by the school gates; what I actually faced was a mountain of paperwork. The school required a food hygiene form for every item, a list of ingredients in case of allergies, and written permission from the caretaker to use the hall on a Saturday. My best friend Priya laughed at my growing folder of documents and said I looked like someone running a small government department rather than a cake stall. Recruiting bakers turned out to be the easy part. Once word spread, offers poured in from unexpected places. Mr Fenwick, our normally stern physics teacher, promised three trays of shortbread, and the school cook, Mrs Adeyemi, offered to supervise anyone who wanted to use the school kitchens after lessons. What nearly sank the whole project was the weather. Two days before the sale, a storm flooded the car park where we had planned to put the overflow tables, and for a few hours I seriously considered cancelling. It was Priya who talked me out of it. She pointed out that we had collected nearly two hundred promised items, that people had already told their families to come, and that moving everything indoors, though cramped, was better than letting everyone down. On the morning itself, I arrived at seven to find a queue already forming, which filled me with equal parts delight and panic. We had decided against fixed prices, asking instead for donations, a suggestion from Mrs Adeyemi that some of my classmates thought was madness. In fact, it proved a stroke of genius. An elderly gentleman handed over twenty pounds for a single slice of lemon cake, explaining quietly that the hospice had cared for his wife the previous year. Moments like that happened all morning, and by noon our cash tins were so heavy that two of us had to carry them together. There were mishaps, of course. Someone's toddler pulled a tablecloth and sent a Victoria sponge sliding to the floor, and we ran out of paper bags within the first hour, forcing customers to balance brownies on napkins. Yet when we counted the takings that evening, we had raised more than triple our target. The head teacher was thrilled, the hospice sent a hand-written card that now hangs in our classroom, and Mr Fenwick's shortbread, to his badly hidden satisfaction, had sold out before nine o'clock. Looking back, I learned that organising anything means drowning in boring details long before you get to the rewarding part. But I also learned something about our town. People do not really come to a bake sale for the cakes, however good the shortbread is. They come because giving feels better when it comes with a paper plate, a chat, and the sense that everyone around you is quietly on the same side.",
