    id: "f-rmc2-03",
    title: "Curtain Up at the Millbrook Players",
    text: "Nobody joins an amateur drama club expecting glamour, but even by our modest standards, the Millbrook Players were struggling when I signed up two years ago. Our rehearsal space was a draughty church hall with a piano that had three silent keys, our costumes lived in suitcases under the chairman's stairs, and our average audience could have travelled home together in a single minibus. So when our director, Gloria, announced that we would stage a full-length musical for the town's summer festival, the committee's reaction ranged from nervous laughter to open horror. Our treasurer, Bernard, produced a spreadsheet showing that the costs of licensing, sets and lighting would empty our account entirely, and warned that a flop would finish the club for good. Gloria listened politely, then said that a club that never risked anything was already finished; it just hadn't noticed yet. The vote went her way by a single hand, mine, raised half in courage and half in confusion. Rehearsals began in February, and the first month was chaos. Our leading man, a retired postman with a genuinely fine voice, could not remember stage directions to save his life, and kept wandering into scenes he wasn't in. Our teenage members, recruited from the local college with the promise of free pizza, treated the schedule as a set of loose suggestions. I had taken on the role of stage manager, which I quickly discovered meant being responsible for everything nobody else wanted to do, from sourcing a working smoke machine to persuading a farmer to lend us hay bales. Yet somewhere around Easter, something shifted. The postman started arriving early to walk his scenes alone. The teenagers, having realised the show was actually going to happen, began turning up on time and even brought friends to help paint scenery. Bernard, our prophet of doom, was discovered one evening quietly repairing a broken throne with wood glue and an expression of deep contentment. The week of the performance brought a crisis that nearly justified all his warnings. On the Tuesday, our leading lady lost her voice completely, and the doctor ordered five days of silence. Gloria neither panicked nor pretended everything was fine. She gathered us in the draughty hall and asked the understudy, a quiet school librarian named Fatima who had never sung a solo in public, whether she was willing. Fatima went pale, took a long breath, and said she hadn't spent four months learning the part to watch the show cancelled. On opening night I stood in the wings with a clipboard I was gripping too hard to read. The hall was full for the first time in the club's history; the festival listing had done its work, and curiosity had done the rest. Fatima's first notes were cautious, but by her second song the audience had stopped comparing her to anyone and started simply listening, and when she finished the applause went on long enough for the band to lose their place. We made a small profit, enough to terrify Bernard slightly less next time. But the real profit was harder to count: a club that had rediscovered why it existed. As Gloria said at the after-party, raising a plastic cup of lukewarm lemonade, theatre isn't about avoiding disaster. It's about finding out who you become while you're dodging it.",
