    id: "f-rmc2-04",
    title: "Grandma and the Blinking Cursor",
    text: "When my grandmother announced at Sunday lunch that she had enrolled in a beginners' coding course at the community centre, my father choked on his roast potato. Grandma Rose is seventy-four, still refers to the television remote as \"the zapper\", and once returned a smartphone to the shop because, in her words, it kept doing things without being asked. The idea of her writing computer programs seemed as likely as her taking up skateboarding. She explained, with the air of someone who had prepared for objections, that the library's local history group wanted to build a website for their archive of old photographs, and that everyone had looked at their shoes when volunteers were requested. Rose, who had spent thirty years cataloguing documents for the county council before retiring, had decided that if a website needed building, she would learn to build it. My father offered, gently, to do it for her. She fixed him with the look that had governed our family for decades and asked why she should let him have all the fun. I became her unofficial homework helper, which taught me more about learning than any of my own teachers ever had. The course used a language called Python, and the early weeks were brutal. Rose would ring me, furious, because the program refused to run over what turned out to be a missing colon. \"In my day,\" she fumed, \"if you filed a document one drawer out of place, a human being could still find it. This machine gives up if a comma sneezes.\" Yet she never once suggested quitting. She kept a hardback notebook, the same kind she had used at the council, in which every error she made was recorded alongside its solution in her immaculate handwriting. When I suggested she could just search online instead, she replied that writing things down was how she made knowledge her own, and that her notebook, unlike the internet, never contradicted itself. What fascinated me was how her age, which everyone had assumed would be her greatest obstacle, turned out in some ways to be an advantage. Her decades of cataloguing had given her an instinct for structure and naming that many young programmers lack. Her tutor, a man in his twenties, admitted that Rose's projects were the tidiest he had ever marked, and that he had started showing her folder organisation to the rest of the class as an example. The younger students, who had initially treated her with careful politeness, began saving her a seat and asking her to check their logic. Six months later, the local history website went online. It is not flashy. It has no animations, and the colour scheme is, frankly, beige. But every one of the four hundred photographs can be found by street name, decade or family, because Rose designed the search the way she had once designed filing systems: for the person looking, not the person building. At the little launch party, someone asked her whether learning to code had made her feel young again. She considered the question seriously, as she considers everything, and said no. It had done something better, she said. It had reminded her that she had never actually stopped being capable, and that the only thing she had ever really retired from was being underestimated.",
