    title: "Bringing the 'Kingfisher' Back to Life",
    text: "The rowing boat had been sitting upside down behind Mr Latimer's garage for as long as any of us could remember, a grey wooden shape that the neighbourhood cats treated as a climbing frame. It was my friend Sam who discovered, while retrieving a football, that a name was still faintly visible on the stern: Kingfisher. When we asked Mr Latimer about it, the old man was quiet for a moment, then told us his father had built the boat by hand in the 1950s and had rowed it on the river every Sunday until his eyesight failed. Mr Latimer himself had always meant to restore it, but his knees were no longer up to kneeling on concrete for hours. Then he looked at the three of us, football still under Sam's arm, and made an offer: if we restored the Kingfisher properly, under his instruction, we could use it whenever we liked. We accepted on the spot, with the total confidence of people who have absolutely no idea what they are agreeing to. I had assumed restoring a boat meant a good scrub and a coat of paint. The reality, as Mr Latimer explained on the first Saturday, was closer to surgery. Several planks had rotted and needed replacing, the seats were split, and every joint had to be checked, cleaned and refastened. Worse, he insisted we do it the traditional way, with hand tools that looked like museum exhibits. When Dev suggested borrowing his dad's electric sander to speed things up, Mr Latimer replied that the boat had waited forty years and could wait a few more months; speed, he said, was how you turned a repair into a ruin. Progress was painfully slow. We worked most weekends through the autumn, and there were plenty of Saturdays when I would rather have stayed in bed. What kept us going, oddly, was not the thought of the finished boat but the work itself. There was something absorbing about planing a plank until it fitted exactly, and Mr Latimer was a patient teacher who never touched our mistakes himself; he would only describe what was wrong and hand the tool back. Dev, who teachers had labelled as someone who couldn't concentrate, would happily spend two hours fairing a single curve. His mum came to watch one Saturday and stayed for the whole afternoon, saying she barely recognised him. We hit our lowest point in January, when we removed a rotten plank and found the frame beneath it was damaged too, doubling the work in that section. Sam argued we should patch it invisibly with modern filler; nobody would ever know. Mr Latimer overheard and said nothing that evening, but the following week he brought out a photograph of his father steaming timber in a homemade rig, and quietly asked us what kind of boat we wanted to be able to say we had made. We replaced the frame properly. It took three weekends. We launched the Kingfisher on the first warm Saturday in May, with Mr Latimer sitting in the stern like a king and half the street watching from the bank. The boat leaked slightly for the first hour, which he assured us was normal until the wood swelled, and then it didn't leak at all. Rowing home into the low evening sun, I understood why his father had gone out every Sunday. Some things you restore turn out, quietly, to restore you back.",
